# Backend Admin — Fastify + Clean Architecture

## Architecture

Three-layer Hexagonal (Ports and Adapters). Dependencies flow **inward only**.

| Layer | Path | Allowed imports |
|---|---|---|
| Core (domain) | `src/core/` | Only other `core/` files, `@shared/`, and `tsyringe` (DI decorators only). ZERO other external packages. |
| Infrastructure (adapters) | `src/infra/` | `core/ports/`, `@shared/`, external SDKs |
| Transport (HTTP) | `src/http/` | `core/use-cases/*/*.types.js` (`import type` only), `core/errors/`, `@shared/`, Fastify types |
| Shared utilities | `src/shared/` | Node.js built-ins only. |
| Config | `src/config/` | `zod`, Node.js built-ins |
| DI container | `src/di/` | Everything (composition root) |

## Admin-Only Service

Every route requires authentication. Three guard levels:

- `adminGuard` — admin role required (most mutation operations)
- `employeeGuard` — admin or employee role (read-heavy/monitoring operations)
- `internalSecretGuard` — X-Internal-Secret header (cron/internal triggers only)

No public routes. No guest access. No storefront routes.

## FORBIDDEN

- Importing from `infra/` in `core/` or `http/`
- `console.log` — use `createLogger()` from `@shared/logger.ts`
- `any` types — use `unknown` and narrow
- Imports inside functions
- `process.env.*` reads outside `config/env.ts`
- Public/unauthenticated routes (except `/health`)
- Business logic in route handlers — routes parse input, call use case, format output
- Direct `@supabase/supabase-js` imports in `core/` or `http/`

## Naming Conventions

- Port interfaces: `admin-xxx-repository.port.ts` → `IAdminXxxRepository`
- Adapters: `supabase-admin-xxx.repository.ts`
- Use cases: `verb-noun.use-case.ts`
- Routes: `xxx.routes.ts`
- Types: `xxx.types.ts`
- Tests: `xxx.test.ts`

## Testing

- **Unit tests** (`test/unit/`): Mock ports, test use case logic
- **Integration tests** (`test/integration/`): `buildTestApp()` + `app.inject()`
- Framework: Vitest

## Marketplace Seller Webhooks

`/webhooks/<provider>/*` callbacks (Eneba, Gamivo, G2A, Kinguin, Digiseller,
Bamboo) live on this Node.js backend, **not** on Supabase Edge Functions.
Per-marketplace wire-format contracts, auth strategies, idempotency rules,
and the test-coverage expectation are documented in
[marketplace-seller-webhooks.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/marketplace-seller-webhooks.mdc).
Read that rule before adding/changing any seller webhook code.
